programme.desc: Canadian divers spot an object that may solve a Cold War nuclear mystery. A mummified businessman is found atop Mexico’s highest peak. In Iceland, a cave said to be home to a fire giant is investigated. Mummified penguins are found in Antarctica.

programme.title: Secrets In The Ice: Mystery Of The Arctic Shipwreck
programme.desc: A Russian mystery involving the deaths of nine hikers may finally be solved. A legendary ship is pulled from icy Arctic waters. In Antarctica, a melting glacier could cause a global disaster. Russian researchers find a strange arrangement of bones.

programme.title: Secrets In The Ice: Mystery Of Glacier Mummy
programme.desc: Mountain climbers in California find the body of a U.S. Army soldier. In Alaska, strange bundles of canvas and wood high up on a mountain are discovered. Volcanic glass is found in an unexpected place. A vital WWII weather station is uncovered.

programme.title: Secrets In The Ice: Ancient Ice Zombies

programme.title: World's Greatest: Ancient Cities
programme.desc: In Ancient Cities, we journey to these ancestors of influence such as Luang Prabang, Vienna, and Istanbul where religious and cultural centers have shaped the ways in which we view the world around us and continue to do so in modern times.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Water Adventures
programme.desc: We are captivated by oceans, rivers, and lakes - the power, the flow, the reflective stillness. And as we seek to get closer, we immerse ourselves in an expanding range of aquatic experiences.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Drives
programme.desc: A journey by road expands our horizons, allowing us to explore the depth and breadth of whole countries and continents, stopping whenever and wherever we chose.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Global Cities
programme.desc: Travel to the centers of wealth, power, industry, and innovation. From London to Tokyo, Hong Kong to New York, these are the cities that never sleep. The influence held in these economic hubs unites the global community.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Island Nations
programme.desc: Though many are small in stature, they have punched well above their weight on the global stage. Some are rooted in ancient history, while others are only just beginning to realize their full potential.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Timeless Cities & Towns
programme.desc: These cities and towns are special places where the past coexists with the present, creating cultures totally unique to their people and their part of the world and adhering to ancient traditions and while introducing modern innovations.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Sacred Sites
programme.desc: Ancient in architecture and detailed in design, these man-made masterpieces stand as testaments to the strength of human faith. These sites endure as a timeless reminder of resilience, respect, and the need to reflect.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Marine Animals
programme.desc: From the surprises of colorful reef characters to effervescent penguins, killer sharks, and regal whales, dive into the places where nature reveals itself in some of its most marvelous and bizarre forms.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Nearshore Islands
programme.desc: Some of the world’s greatest islands are so close that they blend in with the mainland. But regardless of their size and origins, they are often the islands we are drawn to the most, each forging their own unique identity.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Mountains
programme.desc: The earth’s fragile crust has folded and faulted, and nowhere are these natural forces more evident than in the world’s great mountains. Explore the highest peaks of the world’s terrain - the rugged realm between heaven and earth.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Volcanoes
programme.desc: There are few sights on earth as compelling as a volcanic eruption. Volcanoes have the potential to cause death and widespread destruction in a heartbeat, but they also give rise to new life and ecosystems.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Volcanic Islands
programme.desc: They've been worshiped and feared over the millennia. But in the wake of drama and destruction, the elements give rise to cultures and nations so beautiful that we've come to know them as the world's greatest volcanic islands.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Grassland Animals
programme.desc: Grasslands are the great stages of the natural world where large animals play out spectacular lives in clear view of people, including lions, leopards, elephants, rhinoceros, cheetahs, impalas, kangaroos, wallaby, potoroo, bison, and wolves.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Flights
programme.desc: Our experience of the world’s greatest marvels is literally and figuratively elevated when we explore them from the air. Whether you travel by air balloon, helicopter, light aircraft, a grand perspective is always guaranteed.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Extreme Animals
programme.desc: Extreme Animals features environments hostile to humans, but havens to many animals. Witness gorgeous glow-worms, high flying condors, parched thorny devils, emperor penguins, and polar bears in this journey through life on the edge.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Cruises
programme.desc: There is something seductive about setting sail. Cruises offer us a chance to dip our toes into the 70% of our planet awash with oceans, rivers, and lakes, exploring places that can only be reached by daring to leave the shore.

programme.title: World's Greatest: Coral Islands
programme.desc: The reef systems that gave rise to coral islands support the vast majority of marine species on our planet, but they are under threat. Explore the delicate balance between exploiting and preserving these extraordinary natural wonders.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Christine Granville
programme.desc: Christine Granville, aka Krystyna Skarbek, a brave SOE agent, secured the release of captured comrades from the Gestapo before Operation Dragoon, earning the George Medal.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The French Triple Agent
programme.desc: Operation Cockade, led by MI6's double agent Henri Dericourt in 1943, aimed to deceive Germans with sabotage. Despite efforts, Germans withdrew divisions unconvinced. Dericourt faced a post-war treason trial and died in a mysterious 1962 plane crash.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Spymistress and the French Fiasco
programme.desc: After WWII, SOE disbanded, leaving Vera Atkins to uncover fates of 118 agents, including 13 women. Many were betrayed and sent to camps; some were executed. Atkins' quest continued, marked by personal impact and delayed recognition.
programme.sub-title: The Spymistress and the French Fiasco

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The SAS Italian Job
programme.desc: In 1945, during the Italian Spring offensive, SOE agent Michael Lees and SAS officer Roy Farran led a raid on German HQs at Villa Rossi and Villa Calvi. Despite orders to cancel, Farran attacked with SAS men and partisans, killing many Germans.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Dutch Disaster
programme.desc: Operation North Pole was a WWII German deception using captured SOE agents to mislead Britain. 47 of 50 agents were captured. Despite warnings, SOE ignored signs of compromise to maintain support, leading to a major intelligence failure.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Scholar and the Fight for Greece
programme.desc: Monty Woodhouse, a professor and a legend for blowing up the Gorgopotamos Bridge in Greece in 1942. In the British counter attack against Rommell at Al Alamein in North Africa it was vital to disrupt German supply routes, Greece.
programme.sub-title: The Scholar and the Fight for Greece

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Banker, the Norwegians & the Bomb
programme.desc: Sir Charles attended Eton, and then joined the Coldstream Guards. He won the Military Cross on the Western Front and, having survived the war, returned to banking.
programme.sub-title: The Banker, the Norwegians & the Bomb

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Double Agent Tricycle
programme.desc: Dusan Popov was almost certainly James Bond. Ian Fleming knew all the stories about him. Popov managed to persuade both the Germans and MI6 to keep him in the style of a millionaire businessman while performing a series of missions against the Nazis.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Mafia Connection
programme.desc: Lucky Luciano, a mafia boss of the 1930s, was in jail in 1942 on charges of running prostitution rings. US intelligence services did a deal with him and he got the Italians to share intelligence on German U boat movements.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: Hardy Amies and Operation Ratweek
programme.desc: Operation Ratweek’s existence has always been denied. However WMR has now discovered evidence that it existed and was carried out.

programme.title: NEW: Secret War: The Special Interrogation Group
programme.desc: The SIG consisted of German speaking Jewish volunteers from Palestine. They had a highly dangerous job: which was to pose as Germans behind enemy lines and extract intelligence and do acts of sabotage. Few had a long-life expectancy.

programme.title: RAF: The Royal Air Force: Battle for the Skies
programme.desc: In this programme we bring the RAF story into the modern era. Another aircraft to have extended the RAF’s capabilities is the C130 Hercules. This aircraft has proved its capabilities in countless environments from resupply, to dropping paratroopers.

programme.title: RAF: The Royal Air Force: Battle for the Skies
programme.desc: The RAF’s maritime role is often overlooked. Between the wars the RAF operated elegant flying boats to patrol the far flung corners of the Empire.

programme.title: RAF: The Royal Air Force: Battle for the Skies
programme.desc: After the war, RAF transports helped keep Berliners alive during the Soviet blockade of the city in 1948/49. As well as flying round-the-clock operations into the airport, Sunderland flying boats delivered supplies by landing on Lake Havel near the city.

programme.title: RAF: The Royal Air Force: Battle for the Skies
programme.desc: By the end of the First World War the RAF had bombers that could fly to Berlin and back. For the first time in a thousand years British civilians found themselves under direct attack - by Zeppelin airships and Gotha bombers.

programme.title: RAF: The Royal Air Force: Battle for the Skies
programme.desc: By the end of the war the RAF had aircraft that could escort bombers to targets deep inside Germany and back. With the Gloster Meteor, the RAF had also entered the ‘Jet Age’. Aircraft like the Hawker Hunter and F-86 Sabre took the RAF supersonic.

programme.title: RAF: The Royal Air Force: Battle for the Skies
programme.desc: The 1920s and 30s were uncertain times for the RAF as well as all other armed services. With peace came cuts in spending on new aircraft development.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Hidden in Plain Sight 1935-1938
programme.desc: Hidden In Plain Sight 1935-1938: In 1934, Hitler's government is firmly in the saddle. Most Germans support Hitler's anti-Jewish policy and the regime's terror soon escalates.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Up in Flames 1936-1940
programme.desc: Up in Flames 1936-1940: At the end of 1939, the German Army invades Poland. Examine how Hitler succeeded in pushing through his rearmament and war plans relatively unhindered.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Gates of Hell 1941-1942
programme.desc: The Gates of Hell 1941-1942: In the shadow of the war, the Nazi regime gradually advances its "final solution to the Jewish problem", culminating in the Holocaust.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Genocide 1942-1944
programme.desc: Genocide 1942 - 1944: Along with Treblinka and Majdanek, Sobibor was one of the camps used in Operation Reinhard, in which the Nazis murdered almost two million people.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: Armageddon 1943-1945
programme.desc: Armageddon 1943-1945: The defeat at Stalingrad in 1943 was the turning point of the war and convinced the Nazi leadership to intensify their terror and propaganda campaigns.

programme.title: The Abyss: Rise And Fall of The Nazis: The Reckoning 1945-1948

programme.title: 48 Hours: Secrets, Lies and Alibis
programme.desc: John and Susan Sutton were sleeping in separate rooms in their Florida home, when a gunman entered their house and shot both of them several times. Susan was killed, but John survived. Nothing was taken from the house, proving the murder premeditated.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Lost in Paradise
programme.desc: In 1976, Deborah Gardner, a Peace Corps worker, was murdered while on assignment in the South Pacific island nation of Tonga. Dennis Priven, a 24-year-old fellow Peace Corps worker, who appeared to be obsessed with Gardner, was charged by Tongan police.

programme.title: 48 Hours
programme.desc: The investigation into two double murders committed five years apart leads police to a famous hospital and an unlikely suspect.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Amanda Knox: The Untold Story
programme.desc: The story of Amanda Knox, an American exchange student who was convicted, along with her Italian boyfriend, Raffaelle Sollecito, of murdering Amanda’s British roommate, Meredith Kercher in 2007.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Deadly Prophecy
programme.desc: Faylene Eaves, divorced Arizona mother of two, married Doug Grant, a divorced single dad, in 1993. They were both Mormons. Faylene had revelations from God that could have contributed to her death, however her husband was found guilty of murdering her.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Death Wish
programme.desc: A report surrounding the July 2009 death of Jeffrey Locker, whose body was found slumped over the steering wheel of his car in Harlem, New York. When authorities tracked Locker’s ATM card to Kenneth Minor, Minor said Locker had begged Minor to kill him.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Killing Fields
programme.desc: A report about a desolate strip of land between Houston and Galveston where over 30 young women and girls have disappeared or have been murdered.

programme.title: 48 Hours
programme.desc: A report on the investigation into the 1960 murder of Irena Garza, in McAllen, Texas, and the efforts that family members and police have taken to bring the suspect, a Roman Catholic priest, to trial for the crime.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Alternate Suspects
programme.desc: A football coach serves nine years in prison for the murder of his wife before a Texas Court of Criminal Appeals finds he didn't get a fair trial.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Black Dahlia Confidential
programme.desc: The brutal murder in 1947 of Elizabeth Short, a young, struggling actress whose body was discovered in a vacant lot in January 1947, has baffled the Los Angeles Police Department for decades

programme.title: 48 Hours: A Family Torn Apart
programme.desc: The murdered body of Bob Dorotik, a engineer and father of three, was found by a mountain road near his home in the foothills of San Diego, Ca. Despite her denial of any involvement, Jane, Dorotik’s wife of 30 years, was arrested for the crime.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Murder They Wrote: The End of the Dream
programme.desc: A report on the charismatic Scott Scurlock, known as “Hollywood” because of his flamboyant style and effective use of disguises in the commission of crimes, successfully eluded capture for four years while effortlessly robbing 18 banks.
programme.sub-title: Murder They Wrote: The End of the Dream

programme.title: 48 Hours: Accused
programme.desc: In 1996 the car which Sheila Bryan was driving with her mother as passenger accidentally veered off the road and into a ditch killing her mother. Sheila was charged with murder -- then tried, convicted, and sentenced to life imprisonment.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Last Chance
programme.desc: Attorneys work to get a death row inmate who confessed to a crime he didn't commit out of prison.

programme.title: 48 Hours: The Stranger You Know
programme.desc: A report about Marti Hill, who was savagely beaten in her Prairie Village, Kansas home. She was found by police barely breathing and covered in blood.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Temptation in Texas
programme.desc: A report about the 2011 shooting death of Greg Williams, and the question of whether he was killed with his own gun by an intruder inside his suburban Dallas home - as his wife Michele Williams has claimed - or if Michele herself was guilty of the crime.

programme.title: 48 Hours: A Daughter, A Mortgage, and Two Murders
programme.desc: A report on the investigation into the murders of Greg and Bernadette Ohlemacher in 2005. The Albuquerque, New Mexico couple had been shot dead in their home
programme.sub-title: A Daughter, A Mortgage, and Two Murders

programme.title: 48 Hours
programme.desc: A report on the 2009 death of Rhonda Casto, who went hiking in Oregon’s Columbia River Gorge with her boyfriend, Stephen Nichols, and she never returned home.

programme.title: 48 Hours: Fight For The Truth
programme.desc: 17-year-old Marty Tankleff was convicted of murdering his adoptive parents in their home. Marty initially confessed, but quickly recanted. He has fought for years for his innocence, as new witnesses have surfaced who could potentially exonerate him.

programme.title: My Grandmother Ironed The Kings Shirts
programme.desc: Torill Kove's grandmother often told her stories. One in particular revolved around ironing shirts for the King of Norway. And what if that intriguing detail was just the tip of the iceberg?

programme.title: The Way It Is
programme.desc: The Way It Is" explores divorce's effects on a family, centered on twelve-year-old Helen. Her journey to acceptance offers insights for all ages, suitable for family-life courses, single-parent groups, and counseling.

programme.title: Sun Wind And Wood
programme.desc: People combat high energy costs with inventive solar, wind, and wood solutions. This film showcases experiments like the Ark, a bio-shelter sustaining a family with housing, heat, food, and electricity using natural systems.

programme.title: Waiting For Fidel
programme.desc: Three Canadians, including ex-premier Joseph Smallwood and NFB director Michael Rubbo, travel to Cuba, aiming to cast Fidel Castro. Their journey offers insights into Cuba's changes and their own views.

programme.title: Illuminated Lives A Brief History Of Womens Work In The Middle Ages
programme.desc: The popular image of the Middle Ages comes from fairy tales and romances. This animated short challenges some enduring myths about medieval women and shows what their lives were really like.

programme.title: Lipsett Diaries
programme.desc: Lipsett Diaries is a descent into the maelstrom of anguish that tormented famed Canadian experimental filmmaker Arthur Lipsett, who died prematurely at age 49.

programme.title: Walking
programme.desc: Ryan Larkin's "Walking" captures various walking styles through line drawing and color wash techniques. It humorously portrays youth's springy steps, high-heeled minces, and elderly ambles, accompanied by unique sound.

programme.title: The Impossible Takes A Little Longer
programme.desc: Documents the work and personal lives of five physically disabled women. It shows how they are coping with the problems they share with all women, the problems they share with other disabled women and those unique to their particular circumstances.

programme.title: Lay Down Your Heart
programme.desc: An accomplished artist, a lifelong performer and a person with Down syndrome, Niall McNeil has built a unique family tree of blood and chosen relations made up of his closest friends and collaborators.

programme.title: Unwanted Soldiers
programme.desc: Filmmaker Jari Osborne discovers her father's WWII involvement, revealing discrimination against Chinese-Canadians. His secret missions in Southeast Asia shed light on their quiet heroism, paying moving tribute in this multi-layered documentary.

programme.title: Hands Of History
programme.desc: In this acclaimed 1994 documentary, Loretta Todd, a leading figure in Indigenous cinema in Canada, profiles four contemporary female artists.The film is a moving testimony to the vital role Indigenous women play in nurturing Indigenous cultures.

programme.title: Turnaround A Story Of Recovery
programme.desc: Turnaround: A Story of Recovery" follows five women battling addiction at Aurora House. This documentary offers insight for families, friends, and professionals interested in alternative treatment methods.

programme.title: Safe Distance, A
programme.desc: A Safe Distance examines the services needed by and available to battered women. The film looks at some innovative approaches to providing services and accommodation for battered women in rural, northern, and Native communities.

programme.title: Minoru Memory Of Exile
programme.desc: The bombing of the American naval base at Pearl Harbor, by a nation he knew only by name, thrust nine-year-old Minoru Fukushima into a world of racism so malevolent he would be forced to leave Canada, the land of his birth.

programme.title: Bobs Birthday
programme.desc: Surprise birthday parties can be risky. Especially when the guest of honour is turning 40! When Margaret plans a celebration for her husband, Bob, she underestimates the sudden impact of middle age on his mood.

programme.title: Waterwalker
programme.desc: Accompany Bill Mason on a canoe journey through Ontario's wilderness, from Lake Superior to the river's source. Enjoy breathtaking visuals, whitewater excitement, and Mason's reflections on nature, art, and canoeing, with Bruce Cockburn's music.

programme.title: Canada Vignettes The Performer
programme.desc: A vignette featuring Roger Doucet singing O Canada at a hockey game in the Montréal Forum.

programme.title: Doctor Lawyer Indian Chief
programme.desc: A tribute to Indigenous women everywhere, this short documentary focuses on 5 women from across Canada. They talk about the importance of Indigenous culture in helping them to develop a sense of self and seeing through rough times.

programme.title: Neighbours Voisins
programme.desc: Two neighbours live side by side in harmony until a flower grows on the dividing line between their properties. Who does it belong to? The argument that follows ends up with both neighbours in their graves. The most famous of Norman McLaren’s films.

programme.title: Theodore Ushev Unseen Connections
programme.desc: Theodore Ushev, the auteur behind a number of renowned animated shorts, reveals his inner universe, formed by a half-century of personal experience acquired in a constantly changing world.

programme.title: Paul Kane Goes West
programme.desc: in the mid-1800s, Paul Kane painted the northwest, Indigneous Peopless, Chiefs, ceremonies, war parties, buffalo hunts, rapids and waterfalls. In this film his paintings are projected with lighting that brings to life every glowing detail.

programme.title: George And Rosemary
programme.desc: George and Rosemary is an animated romantic comedy about two golden agers who prove that passion is not exclusively for the young.

programme.title: Alphee Of The Stars
programme.desc: Alphée of the Stars puts the spotlight on a most unusual girl. With patience and tenderness, a father – who believes in schools that embrace diversity and do not discriminate – challenges our assumptions and reveals an unknown world.

programme.title: A Love Affair With Politics A Portrait Of Marion Dewar
programme.desc: This spirited documentary on one of Canada's most successful female politicians was filmed while she was mayor of Ottawa. Dewar talks of her political career as a natural extension of her roles of wife, mother, public-health nurse and ordinary citizen.

programme.title: Mountain Of Sgaana
programme.desc: This film spins a magical tale of a young man who is stolen away to the spirit world, and the young woman who rescues him. Haida filmmaker Christopher Auchter’s dream-like gem brilliantly entwines traditional animation with formal elements of Haida art.

programme.title: How They Saw Us Needles And Pins
programme.desc: In this film about a factory seamstress, there is the substitution of glamor for genuine job satisfaction and advancement. The film was made in 1955.

programme.title: Wildes Portugal
programme.sub-title: Von den Bergen bis zur Küste

programme.title: Wildes Portugal
programme.sub-title: Von der Küste bis zu den Inseln
programme.desc: Der Reichtum von Portugals Küstengewässern ist erstaunlich. Tausende von Kreaturen leben am Atlantischen Ozean im Wasser und zu Land. Und die Inselwelt der Azoren mitten im Atlantik ist eines der reichsten Ökosysteme der Welt.

programme.title: Indiens wilde Schönheit: Im Dschungel der Ghats
programme.desc: Von den Himalayas bis zum Ganges, der Lebensader des Landes - Indien ist eine Mischung atemberaubender Landschaften, exotischer Schönheit und faszinierender Tiere. Dieser Film bringt die wilde Seite und Vielfalt Indiens nahe.

programme.title: WILDES ÜBERLEBEN
programme.desc: Für die seltsamsten Lebewesen der Natur kommt es zum Überleben darauf an, mit der Norm auszubrechen. Nur ein bisschen anders zu sein, kann große Vorteile bringen, birgt aber auch große Herausforderungen. Indem sie gegen den Strich gingen, haben diese Tiere einzigartige Wege gefunden, am Leben zu bleiben. Diese Sonderlinge machen das Beste aus ihrer Andersartigkeit und zählen damit zu den größten Überlebenden der Erde.

programme.title: Inseln der Zukunft
programme.desc: Der Film erzählt die Geschichte der Isländer, die von der Natur mit erneuerbaren Energien überreich beschenkt sind und beweisen, dass ein ganzes Land damit versorgt werden kann - und zwar so günstig, dass es zum Problem werden kann.

programme.title: Albanien
programme.desc: Fitim wird von seinen Freunden Elvis genannt, der Elvis von Albanien. Fitim liebt Musik. Manchmal passiert es, dass die Sehnsucht nach der Kindheit zu groß wird, dann kommt er hierher: in das SOS-Kinderdorf am Stadtrand von Tirana.

programme.title: Flucht in die USA
programme.desc: Unsere Dokumentation begleitet Flüchtlinge auf ihrer Odyssee durch mehrere Länder. Und wir begegnen den Helfern der SOS-Kinderdörfer, die auf unterschiedlichste Weise die verzweifelten Familien und deren Kinder unterstützen.

programme.title: Champagner für alle!
programme.desc: Spätsommer, Erntezeit. Die Sonne wärmt mit ihren letzten Strahlen die Spätburgunder-, Schwarzriesling- und Chardonnay-Trauben der Champagne. Hier entsteht der einzigartige französische Schaumwein, gekeltert ausschließlich nach den strengen Regeln der heimischen Winzer: Champagner! Planet Weltweit hat zwei namhafte Champagner-Winzer besucht und spürt der Philosophie der perlenden Lebensfreude nach.

programme.title: Das Land, in dem die Aprikosen blühen
programme.desc: Millionen goldgelber Früchte trocknen in der Sonne. Sie werden auch das Gold aus dem Zweistromland? genannt, die saftigen Aprikosen aus Anatolien. Auf den Plantagen an den Ufern des Euphrat wachsen 95 Prozent aller weltweit verarbeiteten Aprikosen. Doch die Idylle trügt: Hinter der malerischen Fassade brodeln Konflikte mit den alten Patriarchen um mehr Selbstbestimmung, und über allem schwebt die Sorge um die Klimaschwankungen und deren Auswirkungen auf die Ernte. Diese Dokumentation hat nicht nur die Aprikosenernte festgehalten, sondern wurde Zeuge einer Familie im Umbruch.

programme.title: Armeniens Früchte aus dem Paradies
programme.desc: Granatäpfel gehören zu den ältesten Kulturfrüchten der Menschheit. Wissenschaftler glauben sogar, dass der Baum der Erkenntnis? im Alten Testament ein Granatapfelbaum war. In Armenien ist die paradiesische Frucht Nationalsymbol. Das Land gilt als eines der Hauptanbaugebiete weltweit. Die besten Früchte werden im Süden, rund um das Dorf Nrnadzor, geerntet. Mukutsch Bojadyan ist einer der erfolgreichsten Granatapfelbauern des Dorfes. Im Oktober erntet er seine Früchte, nachdem er das ganze Jahr über Wetterkapriolen, Wasserknappheit und Bären getrotzt hat. Planet Weltweit hat ihn und seine Paradiesfrüchte besucht.

programme.title: Stochelo Rosenberg & Peter Beets
programme.desc: The treasured compositions of guitarist Django Reinhardt, the founding father of hot club jazz, are engraved in everyone's memory. Although Reinhardt missed two fingers of his left hand, his virtuoso technique was unrivalled. Dutch guitarist Stochelo Rosenberg and pianist Peter Beets now have the pleasure to bring Django's music back to life with their infectious improvisations.

programme.title: Wes Montgomery
programme.sub-title: Herbie Man & Sonny Sharrock - Memphis underground
programme.desc: This selection of unforgettable performances by some of the most iconic and influential jazz guitarists in history showcases these legends' unique essence. Revel in Wes Montgomery's virtuosity as he performs the captivating “Nica's Dream” in Holland in 1965, and delight in the expressive beauty of his rendition of “Here's That Rainy Day”, recorded in London in that same year. Experience the timeless appeal of Joe Pass's “You Stepped Out of a Dream” and “You Turned The Tables on Me”, recorded live in Hanover in 1975. The interplay between Jim Hall and Atilla Zoller borders on the impossible as they perform “Extensions” in Hanover in 1973. Enjoy Jim Hall's lyrical solo performance of “I'm Getting Sentimental Over You” from 1964. Witness Sonny Sharrock's avant-garde fusion of jazz and rock in an exhilarating performance of “Peanut", recorded live in France in 1970. Sharrock is joined by flutist Herbie Mann in a soulful performance of “Memphis Underground” from 1969. Immerse yourself in the magic of jazz guitar!

programme.title: Buddy Rich, Tom Warrington, Bob Kaye & John Marshall
programme.sub-title: Buddy Rich Big Band - The North Sea Jazz
programme.desc: The North Sea Jazz Festival is the largest indoor music festival in the world, known globally as the event where the past, present and future of jazz are featured within three days. Next to a firm base of jazz as the festival's staple music genre, many others, such as blues, soul, funk, or hip hop, pass by. Buddy Rich, one of the most influential jazz drummers of all time, performed at the North Sea Jazz Festival of 1978 with his orchestra. Rich's drumming was known for its remarkable speed and dexterity, which he achieved without any formal education.

programme.title: Gilberto Gil
programme.desc: Brazilian artist Gilberto Gil returns to Jazz à Vienne in France with a new round of singing that is inspired by his latest album ‘Fé na Festa': a mixture of celebration, tradition and even some rock now and then. Gilberto Gil, worldwide known for as musician and the Brazilian minister of Culture, was one of the pioneers of the cultural movement ‘tropicalismo'. This movement, with a strong character of social protest, combines elements of traditional Brazilian culture with modern art forms. Gilberto Gil's new sound clearly has its roots in Brazilian culture, yet it is always inspired by jazz.

programme.title: Philip Catherine, Jean-Louis Rassinfosse & Chet Baker
programme.sub-title: Jazz a la Grand Place Chet Baker Trio
programme.desc: Two top-tier Belgian musicians – guitarist Philip Catherine and bassist Jean-Louis Rassinfosse – accompany American jazz trumpeter and vocalist Chet Baker during this 1985 performance at the beautiful Brussels Jazz Club, located on the Grand-Place, the Belgian capital's central square. The trio plays Charlie Mariano's “Crystal Bells”, the title track of their acclaimed 1983 album. Other songs played during this legendary concert include “Down” and “How Deep is the Ocean”.

programme.title: David Grimal & Les Dissonances
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 4 in B-flat major, Op. 60
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances perform Ludwig van Beethoven's Symphony No. 4 in B-flat major, Op. 60. Count Franz von Oppersdorff, who adored Beethoven's Symphony No. 2, offered the composer a large sum to write a similar work. Completed in the autumn of 1806, the symphony's first performance was at a private concert in Vienna in March of 1807. Symphony No. 4 is often overshadowed by its revolutionary predecessor and successor. With its lightweight and cheerful nature, Symphony No. 4 contrasts with the two aforementioned works. This performance was recorded at Opéra de Dijon, France, in 2013.

programme.title: David Grimal & Les Dissonances
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances perform Johannes Brahms' String Sextet No. 1 in B-flat major, Op. 18. The work is scored for two violins, two violas, and two cellos. Brahms wrote his only two string sextets at the very beginning of his career. String Sextet No. 1 was written in 1860. Brahms was one of the first to compose for this ensemble, blazing a trail for Antonín Dvořák, Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky, Arnold Schoenberg, and others. This performance was recorded at Opéra de Dijon, France, in 2013.

programme.title: Claudio Abbado, Simón Bolívar Youth Orchestra & Anna Prohaska
programme.desc: Claudio Abbado conducts the Símon Bolívar Youth Orchestra at the Lucerne Easter Festival of 2010. Soloist is the young and talented Austrian soprano Anna Prohaska. On the program are Sergei Prokofiev's “Scythian Suite”, Op. 20, Alban Berg's Lulu Suite for soprano and orchestra, and Pamina's Aria from W. A. Mozart's opera The Magic Flute. The orchestra concludes with a performance of Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky's Symphony No. 6, Op. 74.

programme.title: Gabriela Montero, Youth Orchestra of the Americas & Carlos Miguel Prieto
programme.desc: Venezuelan pianist Gabriela Montero is accompanied by the Youth Orchestra of the Americas conducted by Carlos Miguel Prieto. On the program are Maurice Ravel's Piano Concerto in G Major, as well as two of Montero's own works: the “Latin Concerto” and Improvisations. The performance took place in one of the world's most beautiful concert halls, the Teatro del Lago in Frutillar, located in the middle of the Patagonian plains. The concert hall, which opened its doors in 2010, stands on the banks of Chile's second-largest lake overlooking a volcano that is capped with snow the entire year. In an accompanying interview, Montero speaks about composing, improvising, and performing works of her own alongside those of others. She discusses her home country of Venezuela, where she no longer performs for political reasons.

programme.title: Les Dissonances
programme.sub-title: Mozart - String Quartet No. 19 in C major, K. 465
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances' string quartet – consisting of David Grimal (violin), Hans Peter Hofmann (violin), David Gaillard (viola), and Xavier Phillips (cello) – performs Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart's String Quartet No. 19 in C major, K. 465, ‘Dissonance' (Op. 10 No. 6). The String Quartet is the last in the set of six quartets that were dedicated to Joseph Haydn. Written between 1782 and 1785, these are also known as the Haydn Quartets (Op. 10). String Quartet No. 19 is remarkable for its slow, dissonant introduction, giving the piece its nickname. This ominous passage suddenly gives way to the bright Allegro in C major. This performance was recorded at Opéra Comique in Paris, France, in 2015.

programme.title: Wilde Schönheiten: Das Kaspische Meer
programme.desc: Hinter vergessenen Ländern liegt das größte landumschlossene Gewässer der Welt. Von üppigen Feuchtgebieten zu Steppen, schneebedeckten Bergen zu Wüsten, die Landschaften bieten Herausforderungen für die Kreaturen, die hier leben.

programme.title: Wildes Portugal
programme.sub-title: Vom Flachland bis in die Berge
programme.desc: Portugal ist ein kleines Land, jedoch bekannt für abwechslungsreiche Landschaften. Korkeichenwälder im Süden am Targus-Fluss und bewaldete Berge am Douro-Fluss im Norden. Entsprechend vielfältig ist die Tierwelt, die wir kennenlernen.

programme.title: Wildes Portugal
programme.sub-title: Von den Bergen bis zur Küste
programme.desc: Wasser ist ein Lebenselement, Flüsse sind Lebensadern. Vom Ursprung in den Bergen bis zur Flussmündung lernen wir die Tiere und Landschaften im Herzen Portugals kennen: Hirsche in der Brunft, den seltenen Lynx und den majestätischen Adler.

programme.title: Wildes Portugal
programme.sub-title: Von der Küste bis zu den Inseln
programme.desc: Der Reichtum von Portugals Küstengewässern ist erstaunlich. Tausende von Kreaturen leben am Atlantischen Ozean im Wasser und zu Land. Und die Inselwelt der Azoren mitten im Atlantik ist eines der reichsten Ökosysteme der Welt.

programme.title: Indiens wilde Schönheit: Im Dschungel der Ghats
programme.desc: Von den Himalayas bis zum Ganges, der Lebensader des Landes - Indien ist eine Mischung atemberaubender Landschaften, exotischer Schönheit und faszinierender Tiere. Dieser Film bringt die wilde Seite und Vielfalt Indiens nahe.

programme.title: WILDES ÜBERLEBEN
programme.desc: Für die seltsamsten Lebewesen der Natur kommt es zum Überleben darauf an, mit der Norm auszubrechen. Nur ein bisschen anders zu sein, kann große Vorteile bringen, birgt aber auch große Herausforderungen. Indem sie gegen den Strich gingen, haben diese Tiere einzigartige Wege gefunden, am Leben zu bleiben. Diese Sonderlinge machen das Beste aus ihrer Andersartigkeit und zählen damit zu den größten Überlebenden der Erde.

programme.title: Wilde Schönheiten: Das Kaspische Meer
programme.desc: Hinter vergessenen Ländern liegt das größte landumschlossene Gewässer der Welt. Von üppigen Feuchtgebieten zu Steppen, schneebedeckten Bergen zu Wüsten, die Landschaften bieten Herausforderungen für die Kreaturen, die hier leben.

programme.title: Delfine Hautnah Dreamteams
programme.desc: Im ersten Teil geht es vor allem um die sozialen Strukturen innerhalb einer Delfinschule Großer Tümmler und zwischen Delfinen aus verschiedenen Gruppen. Schon sehr kleine Delfine werden zur Jagd mitgenommen und an den richtigen Gebrauch ihres eigenen Bio- Sonars herangeführt, denn das muss erst erlernt werden. Dabei offenbart sich, dass sich Delfine verschiedener Regionen auf Beute spezialisieren und je nach Beutetier besondere Jagdtechniken anwenden, die von Generation zu Generation weitergegeben werden. Unter Umständen werden sogar Ziel führende Koalitionen mit anderen Meeresbewohnern eingegangen, zum Beispiel mit Stachelrochen. Bei den Großen Tümmlern leben Männchen und Weibchen in getrennten Gruppen. Mittels der Kameraspione können die Werbe- und Paarungsrituale der Großen Tümmler genau beobachtet werden. Die zweite, näher betrachtete Delfinart sind die Spinner- Delfine, bekannt durch ihre waghalsigen Sprünge. Diese Delfinart ist anderen Gruppen der gleichen Art weitaus aufgeschlossener als Große Tümmler und schließt sich gelegentlich zu riesigen Mega- Delfinschulen zusammen, die gemeinsam auf Beutezüge gehen.

programme.title: Delfine Hautnah Freundschaften
programme.desc: Im zweiten Teil der Reihe ist der kleine Delfin aus dem ersten Teil so groß, dass er die mütterliche Delfinschule verlässt. Er ist nun vollkommen auf sich gestellt. Die Kameras begleiten ihn auf der Suche nach Freunden, bei seinen Beutezügen und bei seinem ersten Flirt mit dem anderen Geschlecht. Aber auch andere Delfinarten werden bei ihren Jagdgängen beobachtet und zeigen, wie sehr der Delfin sein Jagdverhalten an die Umgebung, die Jahreszeit und die lokal verfügbare Beute anpassen kann. Orcas lauern den Lachsen bei ihrer alljährlichen Wanderung auf oder wenden geradezu lebensgefährliche Techniken an, um Robben zu fangen. Delfine spüren mittels ihres Sonars Beute im Sand auf oder treiben Fische an Uferbänke, wo sie sie einfach mit einer einmaligen Technik abpflücken. Unterwasseraufnahmegeräte an einem gezähmten Delfin zeigen hautnah, wie Delfine Kontakt zu ihresgleichen aufnehmen. Es wird aber auch gezeigt, dass Delfine viele Dinge tun, um sich zu vergnügen oder ein Spaß zu haben. Und so sieht man sie hier auch beim Surfen und bei einer berauschenden Party.

programme.desc: Unsere Dokumentation begleitet Flüchtlinge auf ihrer Odyssee durch mehrere Länder. Und wir begegnen den Helfern der SOS-Kinderdörfer, die auf unterschiedlichste Weise die verzweifelten Familien und deren Kinder unterstützen.

programme.title: Champagner für alle!
programme.desc: Spätsommer, Erntezeit. Die Sonne wärmt mit ihren letzten Strahlen die Spätburgunder-, Schwarzriesling- und Chardonnay-Trauben der Champagne. Hier entsteht der einzigartige französische Schaumwein, gekeltert ausschließlich nach den strengen Regeln der heimischen Winzer: Champagner! Planet Weltweit hat zwei namhafte Champagner-Winzer besucht und spürt der Philosophie der perlenden Lebensfreude nach.

programme.title: Das Land, in dem die Aprikosen blühen
programme.desc: Millionen goldgelber Früchte trocknen in der Sonne. Sie werden auch das Gold aus dem Zweistromland? genannt, die saftigen Aprikosen aus Anatolien. Auf den Plantagen an den Ufern des Euphrat wachsen 95 Prozent aller weltweit verarbeiteten Aprikosen. Doch die Idylle trügt: Hinter der malerischen Fassade brodeln Konflikte mit den alten Patriarchen um mehr Selbstbestimmung, und über allem schwebt die Sorge um die Klimaschwankungen und deren Auswirkungen auf die Ernte. Diese Dokumentation hat nicht nur die Aprikosenernte festgehalten, sondern wurde Zeuge einer Familie im Umbruch.

programme.title: Armeniens Früchte aus dem Paradies
programme.desc: Granatäpfel gehören zu den ältesten Kulturfrüchten der Menschheit. Wissenschaftler glauben sogar, dass der Baum der Erkenntnis? im Alten Testament ein Granatapfelbaum war. In Armenien ist die paradiesische Frucht Nationalsymbol. Das Land gilt als eines der Hauptanbaugebiete weltweit. Die besten Früchte werden im Süden, rund um das Dorf Nrnadzor, geerntet. Mukutsch Bojadyan ist einer der erfolgreichsten Granatapfelbauern des Dorfes. Im Oktober erntet er seine Früchte, nachdem er das ganze Jahr über Wetterkapriolen, Wasserknappheit und Bären getrotzt hat. Planet Weltweit hat ihn und seine Paradiesfrüchte besucht.

programme.title: [창덕궁 봄꽃 개화 현장] 낙선재 뒷뜰, 돌배나무 풍경
programme.desc: 창덕궁은 태종 때 건립된 조선왕조의 왕궁으로, 처음에는 경복궁의 이궁으로 지어졌지만 경복궁보다 더욱 오래 법궁의 역할을 해왔습니다. 특히 창덕궁 후원은 한국의 유일한 궁궐후원이라는 점에서 그 가치가 매우 높지요. 한국의 대표적인 정원인 창덕궁이 봄을 맞이하는 아름다운 모습을 감상해보세요! ※ 창덕궁 (사적 제122호, 1997년 유네스코 세계문화유산)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: [오늘도 평화로운 갯벌] 바람에 흔들리는 갈대숲, 순천만
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널순천만은 남해안 중서부에 위치한 만으로, 갯벌에 펼쳐지는 갈대밭과 칠면초 군락 등이 어우러져 아름다운 해안 생태경관을 보입니다. 넓은 갯벌에는 다양한 갯벌 생물들이 살고, 천연기념물인 흑두루미를 비롯한 국제 희귀 조류가 찾는 순천만의 풍경을 감상해 보세요! ※ 전라남도 순천시 순천만 (명승 제41호) / 한국의 갯벌 (2021년 유네스코 세계자연유산)

programme.title: [신비롭고 아름다운 비경] 청송 주산지 EP.3
programme.desc: 자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널주산지는 조선 경종(1720년) 10월에 준공하였습니다. 주산지의 맑은 물은 주산현 꼭대기 별바위에서 계곡을 따라 흘러 주산지에 머무르고 주왕산 영봉에서 뻗친 울창한 수림으로 둘러싸여 있으며, 물위에 떠있는 듯한 왕버들과 어우러져 별천지에 온 것 같이 한적하면서도 아늑한 분위기를 자아냅니다. ※ 청송 주산지 일원 (명승 제 105호) / 청송세계지질공원 (2017년 유네스코 세계지질공원)

programme.title: [궁궐 속 비밀의 화원] 창덕궁 낙선재 후원 EP.5
programme.desc: 낙선재는 헌종 대에 지어진 건물로, 사대부 주택의 형식을 따랐으나 궁궐 침전의 양식이 가미되었습니다. 때문에 다른 곳에서는 쉽게 찾아볼 수 없는 다양한 문양의 장식이 있어 조선 후기 건축의 축적된 기량을 엿볼 수 있죠. 일반인 비공개 지역인 창덕궁 낙선재 후원을 바라보며 휴식을 취해보세요. ※ 창덕궁 낙선재 (보물 1764호) / 창덕궁 (1997년 유네스코 세계문화유산)자료 제공 : 국가유산청, 국가유산진흥원, 국가유산채널

programme.title: 조선 도예의 맥을 잇다. 사기장

programme.title: Stochelo Rosenberg & Peter Beets
programme.desc: The treasured compositions of guitarist Django Reinhardt, the founding father of hot club jazz, are engraved in everyone's memory. Although Reinhardt missed two fingers of his left hand, his virtuoso technique was unrivalled. Dutch guitarist Stochelo Rosenberg and pianist Peter Beets now have the pleasure to bring Django's music back to life with their infectious improvisations.

programme.title: Wes Montgomery
programme.sub-title: Herbie Man & Sonny Sharrock - Memphis underground
programme.desc: This selection of unforgettable performances by some of the most iconic and influential jazz guitarists in history showcases these legends' unique essence. Revel in Wes Montgomery's virtuosity as he performs the captivating “Nica's Dream” in Holland in 1965, and delight in the expressive beauty of his rendition of “Here's That Rainy Day”, recorded in London in that same year. Experience the timeless appeal of Joe Pass's “You Stepped Out of a Dream” and “You Turned The Tables on Me”, recorded live in Hanover in 1975. The interplay between Jim Hall and Atilla Zoller borders on the impossible as they perform “Extensions” in Hanover in 1973. Enjoy Jim Hall's lyrical solo performance of “I'm Getting Sentimental Over You” from 1964. Witness Sonny Sharrock's avant-garde fusion of jazz and rock in an exhilarating performance of “Peanut", recorded live in France in 1970. Sharrock is joined by flutist Herbie Mann in a soulful performance of “Memphis Underground” from 1969. Immerse yourself in the magic of jazz guitar!

programme.title: Buddy Rich, Tom Warrington, Bob Kaye & John Marshall
programme.sub-title: Buddy Rich Big Band - The North Sea Jazz
programme.desc: The North Sea Jazz Festival is the largest indoor music festival in the world, known globally as the event where the past, present and future of jazz are featured within three days. Next to a firm base of jazz as the festival's staple music genre, many others, such as blues, soul, funk, or hip hop, pass by. Buddy Rich, one of the most influential jazz drummers of all time, performed at the North Sea Jazz Festival of 1978 with his orchestra. Rich's drumming was known for its remarkable speed and dexterity, which he achieved without any formal education.

programme.title: Gilberto Gil
programme.desc: Brazilian artist Gilberto Gil returns to Jazz à Vienne in France with a new round of singing that is inspired by his latest album ‘Fé na Festa': a mixture of celebration, tradition and even some rock now and then. Gilberto Gil, worldwide known for as musician and the Brazilian minister of Culture, was one of the pioneers of the cultural movement ‘tropicalismo'. This movement, with a strong character of social protest, combines elements of traditional Brazilian culture with modern art forms. Gilberto Gil's new sound clearly has its roots in Brazilian culture, yet it is always inspired by jazz.

programme.title: Philip Catherine, Jean-Louis Rassinfosse & Chet Baker
programme.sub-title: Jazz a la Grand Place Chet Baker Trio
programme.desc: Two top-tier Belgian musicians – guitarist Philip Catherine and bassist Jean-Louis Rassinfosse – accompany American jazz trumpeter and vocalist Chet Baker during this 1985 performance at the beautiful Brussels Jazz Club, located on the Grand-Place, the Belgian capital's central square. The trio plays Charlie Mariano's “Crystal Bells”, the title track of their acclaimed 1983 album. Other songs played during this legendary concert include “Down” and “How Deep is the Ocean”.

programme.title: David Grimal & Les Dissonances
programme.sub-title: Beethoven - Symphony No. 4 in B-flat major, Op. 60
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances perform Ludwig van Beethoven's Symphony No. 4 in B-flat major, Op. 60. Count Franz von Oppersdorff, who adored Beethoven's Symphony No. 2, offered the composer a large sum to write a similar work. Completed in the autumn of 1806, the symphony's first performance was at a private concert in Vienna in March of 1807. Symphony No. 4 is often overshadowed by its revolutionary predecessor and successor. With its lightweight and cheerful nature, Symphony No. 4 contrasts with the two aforementioned works. This performance was recorded at Opéra de Dijon, France, in 2013.

programme.title: David Grimal & Les Dissonances
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances perform Johannes Brahms' String Sextet No. 1 in B-flat major, Op. 18. The work is scored for two violins, two violas, and two cellos. Brahms wrote his only two string sextets at the very beginning of his career. String Sextet No. 1 was written in 1860. Brahms was one of the first to compose for this ensemble, blazing a trail for Antonín Dvořák, Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky, Arnold Schoenberg, and others. This performance was recorded at Opéra de Dijon, France, in 2013.

On the program are Sergei Prokofiev's “Scythian Suite”, Op. 20, Alban Berg's Lulu Suite for soprano and orchestra, and Pamina's Aria from W. A. Mozart's opera The Magic Flute. The orchestra concludes with a performance of Pyotr Ilyich Tchaikovsky's Symphony No. 6, Op. 74.

programme.title: Gabriela Montero, Youth Orchestra of the Americas & Carlos Miguel Prieto
programme.desc: Venezuelan pianist Gabriela Montero is accompanied by the Youth Orchestra of the Americas conducted by Carlos Miguel Prieto. On the program are Maurice Ravel's Piano Concerto in G Major, as well as two of Montero's own works: the “Latin Concerto” and Improvisations. The performance took place in one of the world's most beautiful concert halls, the Teatro del Lago in Frutillar, located in the middle of the Patagonian plains. The concert hall, which opened its doors in 2010, stands on the banks of Chile's second-largest lake overlooking a volcano that is capped with snow the entire year. In an accompanying interview, Montero speaks about composing, improvising, and performing works of her own alongside those of others. She discusses her home country of Venezuela, where she no longer performs for political reasons.

programme.title: Les Dissonances
programme.sub-title: Mozart - String Quartet No. 19 in C major, K. 465
programme.desc: Les Dissonances is a collective of artists founded by violinist David Grimal in 2004. The conductorless ensemble consists of musicians from the most prestigious European orchestras, international soloists, and young talents. In this performance, Les Dissonances' string quartet – consisting of David Grimal (violin), Hans Peter Hofmann (violin), David Gaillard (viola), and Xavier Phillips (cello) – performs Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart's String Quartet No. 19 in C major, K. 465, ‘Dissonance' (Op. 10 No. 6). The String Quartet is the last in the set of six quartets that were dedicated to Joseph Haydn. Written between 1782 and 1785, these are also known as the Haydn Quartets (Op. 10). String Quartet No. 19 is remarkable for its slow, dissonant introduction, giving the piece its nickname. This ominous passage suddenly gives way to the bright Allegro in C major. This performance was recorded at Opéra Comique in Paris, France, in 2015.
